#### Textual length/complexity

_Umineko_ is really long and complex. The total has been estimated at 1.3 million words, there's something like 63 characters spread over at least 12 discrete storytelling units, with 7 or more different scenarios played out. I was curious how it compared.

A simple word count is not necessarily appropriate: the script is mostly dialogue, which is repetitive compared to your normal novel. In the spirit of the [Hutter Prize](http://prize.hutter1.net/) & Burfoot's ["Notes on a New Philosophy of Empirical Science"](http://arxiv.org/abs/1104.5466), a better way might be to approximate the entropy of the various works by examining their *compressed* sizes. (Another example of this approach is [comparing _Dubliners_ to _Ulysses_](http://www.joyofdata.de/blog/relation-of-word-order-and-compression-ratio/ "Relation of Word Order and Compression Ratio and Degree of Structure").)

The most powerful general-purpose and widely-available lossless compression tool I know of is the [`xz`](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Xz) implementation of [LZMA](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lempel%E2%80%93Ziv%E2%80%93Markov_chain_algorithm) (`sudo apt-get install xz-utils`). It's not as good as the highly-tuned LZMA variants being used in the Hutter compression contest, but `xz` is the most powerful widely-available standard form of LZMA I know of and so it's a better choice than more familiar compression tools like `gzip`.

The _Umineko_ HTML scripts for episodes 1-6 (minus 7 and 8) are downloaded from the Internet Archive; the _Wheel of Time_ PDFs are downloaded from [Libgen](http://libgen.org/search.php?req=%22wheel+of+time%22) (except the last, _A Memory of Light_, which is apparently unavailable). We extract the text:

~~~{.Bash}
$ elinks -dump http://web.archive.org/web/20111001132503/http://jbcs.info/Umineko/ep1.html \
               http://web.archive.org/web/20111001132540/http://jbcs.info/Umineko/ep2.html \
               http://web.archive.org/web/20110930122736/http://jbcs.info/Umineko/ep3.html \
               http://web.archive.org/web/20111001132610/http://jbcs.info/Umineko/ep4.html \
               http://web.archive.org/web/20110919085338/http://jbcs.info/Umineko/ep5.html \
               http://web.archive.org/web/20111001112156/http://jbcs.info/Umineko/ep6.html > umineko.txt
$ wget http://www.gutenberg.org/ebooks/100.txt.utf-8 -O shakespeare.txt
$ emacs -nw shakespeare.txt # manually edit out header, footer, copyright notice in between works
$ dos2unix *

$ for file in Robert*.pdf \(Wheel*\)*.pdf; do pdftotext "$file"; done
$ cat Robert*.txt \(Wheel*\)*.txt > wot.txt && rm *.pdf
~~~

A compressed (8.8M) tarball of these files has been [uploaded to Dropbox](http://dl.dropboxusercontent.com/u/182368464/umineko-compress.tar.xz) if anyone wants to play around with it.

With these new files, we can look at their uncompressed sizes:

~~~{.Bash}
$ du -h *
5.1M    shakespeare.txt
5.4M    umineko.txt
21M wot.txt
32M total
$ wc *
  121809   883317  5327372 shakespeare.txt
  107853   885597  5651767 umineko.txt
  295640  3928775 21638965 wot.txt
  525302  5697689 32618104 total
~~~

_WoT_ = 3928775; this is consistent with [Wikipedia](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Wheel_of_Time#Books_in_the_series)'s overall estimate of 4056130 total words (if _AMoL_ is ~360k). So far so good.

Now let's do the compression and see:

~~~{.Bash}
for book in *
do
    echo "$book"

    echo "Gzip (min): "; cat $book | gzip -1 --stdout - | wc --bytes
    echo "Gzip (max): "; cat $book | gzip -9 --stdout - | wc --bytes

    ## commented out because bzip2 insists on printing junk which clutters the output
    # echo "Bzip2 (min): "; cat $book | bzip2 -1 --stdout --compress --quiet | wc --bytes
    # echo "Bzip2 (max): "; cat $book | bzip2 -9 --stdout --compress --quiet | wc --bytes

    echo "LZMA (min): "; cat $book | xz -0 --stdout | wc --bytes
    echo "LZMA (max): "; cat $book | xz -9 --extreme --stdout | wc --bytes
done
~~~

Output:

    shakespeare.txt
    Gzip (min):
    2347161
    Gzip (max):
    1967186
    LZMA (min):
    2124932
    LZMA (max):
    1549296

    umineko.txt
    Gzip (min):
    2351850
    Gzip (max):
    1929022
    LZMA (min):
    2103496
    LZMA (max):
    1427424

    wot.txt
    Gzip (min):
    9796842
    Gzip (max):
    8216241
    LZMA (min):
    8895168
    LZMA (max):
    5905940

_Umineko_ vs the compleat Shakespeare:

1427424 / 1549296 = 92%

Versus _WoT_:

1427424 / 5905940 = 24%

So we see that _Umineko_ contains somewhere around as much entropy as Shakespeare (Shakespeare is shorter, but harder to compress, as one expects), but for sheer bulk, can't compete with _WoT_, which makes sense to me: I don't think I could read _WoT_ in just 70 hours unless I skimmed a lot of it - those books are gargantuan!
